end for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."],"variants":[{"name":"Heribert","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. An Old English form, <i>Herebeorht</i>, existed in England before the Conquest, but was superseded by the Norman form, which gave rise to an important surname. The family in question were earls of Pembroke in the 16th and 17th centuries; they included the poet  George Herbert . By the end of the Middle Ages <i>Herbert</i> was little used, although it remained a favourite with some families, notably the Saint Quintins of East Yorkshire. Its greater frequency in Britain from the 19th century onwards is due partly to the trend for the revival of medieval names of Germanic origin and partly to the trend for the transferred use of surnames."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Herbert de Orreby III was born in 1063, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Herbert de Orreby II, was 24 and his mother, Agnes de Orreby, was 22. He married Mrs. Herbert de Orreby. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1063–":"1063–Surnud","1063–Male":"1063–Surnud","1063–Female":"1063–Surnud","1089–Male":"1089–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1039–1080":"1039–1080","1041–Female":"1041–Surnud","1080":"1080","1039":"1039","1089":"1089","1063":"1063","um 1089":"umbes 1089","1041":"1041","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Orby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Orby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1063–":"1063–Kuollut","1063–Male":"1063–Kuollut","1063–Female":"1063–Kuollut","1089–Male":"1089–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1039–1080":"1039–1080","1041–Female":"1041–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1039":"1039","1089":"1089","1063":"1063","um 1089":"noin 1089","1041":"1041","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Orby, Lin